        <h2>GeoWorks Ensemble</h2>
        <p>In 1990, GeoWorks released GEOS for IBM PC compatible systems, PC/GEOS.</p>
        <p>Also called GeoWorks Ensemble, it was incompatible with the earlier 8-bit versions of GEOS for Commodore and Apple II computers, but provided numerous enhancements, including scalable fonts and multitasking even on {'XT'|link_urls:'i'} and {'AT'|link_urls:'i'} class PC clones.</p>
        <p>GeoWorks saw a market opportunity to provide a graphical user interface for the 16 million older model PCs that were unable to run Microsoft {'Windows 2'|link_urls:'i'}.</p>
        <p>GEOS was packaged with a suite of productivity applications.</p>
        <p>Each had a name prefixed by "Geo": <strong>GeoWrite</strong>, <strong>GeoDraw</strong>; <strong>GeoManager</strong>; <strong>GeoPlanner</strong>; <strong>GeoDex</strong>, and <strong>GeoComm</strong>.</p>
        <p>It was also bundled with numerous PCs at the time, but like other {'GUI'|link_urls:'i'} environments for the PC platform, such as {'GEM'|link_urls:'i'}, it ultimately proved less successful in the marketplace than {'Windows'|link_urls:'i'}.</p>
        <p>Former CEO of GeoWorks claims that GEOS faded away because Microsoft threatened to withdraw supply of {'MS-DOS'|link_urls:'i'} to hardware manufacturers who bundled Geoworks with their machines.</p>
        <p>Even though PC/GEOS is referred to as an "operating system", it still requires {'DOS'|link_urls:'i'} software in order to load.</p>
        <p>GEOS and its applications were written in a mix of {'8086'|link_urls:'i'} {'assembly language'|link_urls:'/l'} and {'C'|link_urls:'/l'}.</p>  
